# ============================================================
# Cursor Rules — AI Project with Image Manipulation
# ============================================================

## 🧠 Project Context
This is an AI-powered application that performs image manipulation tasks
(e.g., generation, editing, filtering, segmentation, inpainting, style transfer).
Code must be clean, performant, and safe for production AI/ML workloads.

---

## 🗂️ Project Structure

```
src/
  ai/           # AI model loading, inference, pipelines
  image/        # Core image processing utilities
  api/          # API routes / server handlers
  ui/           # Frontend components (if applicable)
  utils/        # Shared helpers
  config/       # Config files and constants
  types/        # TypeScript types / Pydantic models
tests/
  unit/
  integration/
assets/         # Static assets, test images
scripts/        # One-off scripts, batch processing
```

---

## 🐍 Python Rules (Backend / ML)

### General
- Use Python 3.10+ features (match statements, type unions with `|`)
- All functions must have type hints — no bare `Any` unless unavoidable
- Use `pathlib.Path` instead of `os.path` for all file operations
- Prefer `dataclasses` or `pydantic` models over raw dicts for structured data
- Use `__all__` in module files to define public API

### AI / Model Code
- Always wrap model inference in a dedicated class (e.g., `class ImagePipeline`)
- Separate model loading from inference: `load()` vs `run()` methods
- Use `torch.no_grad()` or `@torch.inference_mode()` for all inference calls
- Never load a model inside a request handler — always load at startup
- Log model load time and memory usage on initialization
- Use `device = torch.device("cuda" if torch.cuda.is_available() else "cpu")` pattern
- Support both FP32 and FP16 (`model.half()`) with a config flag
- Always validate inputs before passing to model (shape, dtype, value range)

### Image Processing
- Work in float32 internally; convert to uint8 only for output/storage
- Normalize images to [0, 1] unless a model explicitly expects [0, 255] or [-1, 1]
- Document the expected input/output range in every image function's docstring
- Use PIL for simple I/O and transforms; use OpenCV for performance-critical ops
- Use NumPy for array manipulation; avoid nested Python loops on pixel data
- Always check image shape before processing: `assert img.ndim == 3`
- Handle both RGB and RGBA; explicitly convert when needed
- Never mutate input images in-place — return new arrays/tensors
- Use context managers for large temporary buffers: `with torch.cuda.memory_efficient_sdp_enabled():`

### Async & Concurrency
- Use `asyncio` for I/O-bound tasks (file reads, HTTP calls)
- Use thread pools (`concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor`) for CPU-bound image tasks
- Never run blocking model inference in the async event loop — use `run_in_executor`
- Implement job queuing (e.g., with Celery or asyncio.Queue) for heavy workloads

### Error Handling
- Raise typed exceptions (create custom exceptions in `src/exceptions.py`)
- Catch and wrap library errors (Pillow `UnidentifiedImageError`, etc.) with context
- Never silently swallow exceptions in image pipelines
- Return `Result` types or raise for API-boundary functions — be consistent

---

## ⚡ TypeScript / JavaScript Rules (Frontend / Node)

### General
- Use TypeScript strict mode: `"strict": true` in tsconfig
- Prefer `const` over `let`; never use `var`
- Use named exports, not default exports (except for Next.js pages/layouts)
- All async functions must handle errors with try/catch or `.catch()`

### Image Handling
- Use `<img>` with explicit `width` and `height` to prevent layout shift
- Always set `alt` text on images for accessibility
- Use `URL.createObjectURL()` for client-side image previews; revoke with `URL.revokeObjectURL()` when done
- Use `canvas` API for client-side image transformations — never mutate DOM images directly
- Use `HTMLCanvasElement.toBlob()` (async) over `toDataURL()` for large images
- Compress previews before sending to API — target < 2MB for uploads
- Show skeleton loaders or progress bars during AI processing — never leave UI frozen

### API Calls
- Type all API request/response shapes with interfaces
- Use `FormData` for multipart image uploads
- Implement request cancellation (`AbortController`) for long-running image jobs
- Handle `413 Payload Too Large` and display user-friendly error messages

---

## 🔌 API Design Rules

- Use RESTful conventions: `POST /images/process`, `GET /images/{id}/status`
- Accept images as multipart/form-data OR base64 JSON — support both
- Always validate file type (check magic bytes, not just extension)
- Enforce file size limits (default: 10MB) and return `413` with a clear message
- Return job IDs for long operations; use polling or WebSocket for status
- Include processing metadata in responses: `model`, `duration_ms`, `input_size`
- Use structured logging (JSON) for all requests with `image_id`, `operation`, `duration`

---

## 🔒 Security Rules

- Validate all uploaded files — check MIME type AND magic bytes
- Sanitize filenames — never use user-provided names for filesystem paths
- Limit max image dimensions (e.g., 4096×4096) to prevent DoS
- Scan for malicious content in SVGs and animated GIFs
- Use signed URLs or tokens for output image storage
- Never log image content or base64 data — log metadata only
- Rate-limit image generation endpoints (e.g., 10 req/min per user)

---

## 🧪 Testing Rules

- Unit test every image utility function with multiple input shapes/dtypes
- Include edge cases: empty images, single-pixel, very large (4K), unusual aspect ratios
- Test with both CPU and GPU paths (mock CUDA if unavailable in CI)
- Use `pytest-benchmark` for performance regression tests on core transforms
- Test model inference with known inputs and expected outputs (snapshot tests)
- Ensure consistent output: same input → same output (seed control for generative models)

---

## 📦 Dependencies & Environment

- Pin all ML dependencies (torch, diffusers, transformers) to exact versions
- Use virtual environments; document CUDA version in README
- Never commit model weights — reference by URL/hash in config
- Use `.env` files for API keys and model paths; never hardcode secrets
- Document GPU memory requirements per model in comments

---

## 🚀 Performance Rules

- Cache loaded models — never reload per request
- Use batching for multiple image requests when possible
- Resize images to model's expected resolution before inference, not after
- Profile with `torch.profiler` or `cProfile` before optimizing
- Use ONNX Runtime or TorchScript for production inference when possible
- Log slow operations (>500ms) with a warning

---

## 📝 Documentation Rules

- Every public function needs a docstring: purpose, params, return value, exceptions
- Document image format expectations: shape `(H, W, C)`, dtype, value range
- Include example input/output in docstrings for non-trivial transforms
- Add a `# NOTE:` comment explaining any non-obvious mathematical operations
- Keep a `CHANGELOG.md` updated with model version bumps

---

## 🎨 Code Style

- Max line length: 100 characters
- Use `ruff` for Python linting and `black` for formatting
- Use `eslint` + `prettier` for TypeScript
- Commit messages: `type(scope): description` (e.g., `feat(pipeline): add inpainting support`)
- Branch naming: `feature/`, `fix/`, `experiment/`, `chore/`

---

## ⛔ Anti-Patterns to Avoid

- ❌ Loading models on every request
- ❌ Using raw pixel loops in Python (use vectorized NumPy/PyTorch ops)
- ❌ Storing generated images in memory indefinitely — use TTL/cleanup jobs
- ❌ Ignoring image orientation EXIF data (causes subtle rotation bugs)
- ❌ Assuming all images are RGB — always check and convert explicitly
- ❌ Hard-coding model paths or API keys
- ❌ Using `print()` for debugging in production code — use `logging`
- ❌ Returning raw tensor objects from API functions — convert to numpy/PIL first
